      <div class="text-container left">
        <h2>The News Crisis</h2>
          <p class="text left">The global recession in 2008 and 2009 put increased pressure on an already declining commercial print and broadcast news industry. Faced with declining circulation, advertising losses and a new wave of digital competitors, the news industry struggled mightily. Texas certainly wasn’t spared. The reporting corps in the statehouse had dwindled, and options for in-depth coverage of state politics and public policy were quickly drying up.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="text-container right">
        <h2>A New Way</h2>
          <p class="text right">Texas Tribune founders John Thornton and Evan Smith believed nonpartisan news and information was too crucial a component of a functioning democracy to be left exclusively to market forces.<br><br>They sought to build a nonprofit alternative that would make Texas a better, healthier, more vibrant place.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="text-container left">
        <h2 >Introducing the Texas Tribune</h2>
          <p class="text left">The Texas Tribune is a nonpartisan, nonprofit media organization that informs Texans — and engages with them — about public policy, politics, government and statewide issues.<br><br>This fall marks the Tribune’s fifth year of providing free award-winning journalism, standing-room-only events and in-depth public data interactives. </p>
